name: Starbucks

comment: One bathroom is not very wheelchair accessible (the one to your right if you're facing the register) due to storage and customer seating nearby.

name: Salon On The Square
directions: To the left side of the salon down a short hallway.
comment:
This is a locally-owned salon that specializes in Creative color and counterculture hairstyles. They are staffed almost entirely by gay employees & LGBTQ friendly employees.

If you are feeling threatened or unsafe while walking around the square, ask for Brandon, Shannon, or Callie. Explain your situation and they can pretend to be talking to you about what you are looking to get done for your next cut and color until you are safe.

name: Jammin Java coffee shop
directions: In the back of the coffee shop to the right, by the kitchen.
comment:
Small locally owned coffee shop, staff and clientele usually fairly liberal hippie types :)

Single genderfree bathroom with 1 toilet.
It would be a nice gesture to buy a soda or a small coffee or something, but they don't insist.

name: Little Bread Co.
directions: In the back of the dining room to the right, small single genderfree restroom, one toilet.
comment: Locally owned bakery, very liberal and LBGTQ friendly atmosphere, frequented mostly by the "weird locals" crowd.

name: Ozark Natural Foods
directions: In back left of store, always kept very nice.
comment: This store is a organic grocery and supplement store that has publicly come out in support of civil rights for all genders.

name: Costa Coffee
directions: Towards the back of the coffee shop there is a door indicating to the toilets, you go through that and upstairs - there will be 2 gender neutral restrooms to your right. Also, towards the back of the shop there is a unisex accessible toilet which remains downstairs and has access for everyone.
comment: I have never seen anybody get pulled up for using these toilets without purchasing a drink, but do be wary as they may pull you up if the shop is quiet.

name: The Hut
directions: Enter the building and go right once you've walked past the reception desk - there are two single-stalled gendered toilets near the lockers.
comment: The Hut is part of the safer places schemes and are very considering of the LGBT* community, they have LGBT groups as well as some transgender staff members. If the single stalls are taken, there is a unisex bathroom upstairs which can be accessed with permission.

name: The Hut

comment: Part of the safer places scheme, also have transgender members of staff. The centre are very supportive of the LGBT* community.

name: University of Texas at El Paso (UTEP)
directions: located in the Union West building on the second floor around food court area. Bathroom is right across from "Pick 'n' Shovel" student buffet and is welcoming to both genders and transgender people
comment: Bathroom's are welcoming to both transgender men and women who don't feel comfortable having to go to the bathroom of their birth gender

name: Carr Hall
directions:
Ground floor, roughly about the middle of the building. Signs posted on doors into the building.

Also bathrooms on the upper floors - take the east stairs up - third floor women's, fourth floor men's. There is also an elevator on the west side of the building - you can take this up to the floor, and then follow the hallway through the building to the other side where the washrooms are.
comment:
Inside a University of Toronto Building. They are two stalls to a washroom, but hardly used (especially the ones on the upper floors).

This is semi-accessiable. Both the washrooms on the ground floor, and the ones on the upper floors, do not have wide wheelchair stalls.
